# Interface Diligence Artifact Backend — Privacy Policy

Effective Date: June 25, 2026

This Privacy Policy explains how the Interface Diligence Artifact Backend handles data when used with Interface Diligence Custom GPT agents.

This backend supports a semi-automated diligence workflow. The Custom GPT agents perform reasoning inside ChatGPT. The backend only creates isolated runs, stores artifacts, tracks phase status, and exposes saved outputs to authorized workflow agents.

## 1. Who operates this backend

The Interface Diligence Artifact Backend is operated by Lex Nova HQ / Interface Diligence.

For privacy questions, contact: [INSERT CONTACT EMAIL]

## 2. What data is processed

When a reviewer uses an Interface Diligence GPT agent, the backend may receive and store:

* target name, company name, domain, or URL;
* reviewer-provided public source material;
* pasted text supplied by the reviewer;
* metadata about uploaded public PDF, DOC, or TXT material where supplied through the workflow;
* generated diligence artifacts, including source discovery, legal cartography, target profile, feature profile, data provenance, exposure registry, challenge gate, final handoff, terminal validation, and renderer payloads;
* run identifiers, phase status, lock status, timestamps, and workflow logs;
* API request metadata necessary to operate and secure the backend.

The backend is designed for public-footprint diligence and reviewer-authorized material. Reviewers should not submit private, confidential, privileged, personal, sensitive, or restricted material unless they are authorized to do so and understand that it may be stored as part of the run.

## 3. How data is used

Data is used only to:

* create and isolate diligence runs;
* save workflow artifacts under an exact run ID;
* allow authorized downstream agents to retrieve required artifacts;
* prevent cross-run contamination;
* support the portfolio renderer or final report view;
* debug, audit, secure, and operate the workflow.

The backend does not sell personal data.

The backend does not use stored artifacts to train AI models.

The backend does not itself call OpenAI, Gemini, or other model APIs for reasoning. Reasoning happens inside the Custom GPT conversation controlled by the reviewer.

## 4. Third-party infrastructure

The backend may use third-party cloud infrastructure and storage services, including:

* Google Cloud Run;
* Google Firestore;
* Google Drive;
* Google Sheets;
* OpenAI Custom GPT Actions.

When a Custom GPT uses an Action, relevant parts of the reviewer’s input or generated artifact may be sent from ChatGPT to this backend so the requested workflow step can be completed.

## 5. Run isolation

Each run is scoped by an exact `run_id`.

The backend is designed to prevent retrieval by company name, domain name, “latest run,” or similar loose lookup. Artifacts should be read or written only by exact `run_id` and authorized `artifact_name`.

## 6. Access controls

Workflow agents have scoped permissions.

Agent 1 may save only:

* `source_discovery_handoff`;
* `legal_cartography_index`.

Agent 1 does not have permission to read prior artifacts.

Downstream agents may read only the artifacts required for their assigned workflow phase.

## 7. Retention

Artifacts and run records may be retained for operational, audit, debugging, and report-rendering purposes unless deleted or superseded.

A reviewer or authorized operator may request deletion of a run or artifact by contacting the operator at the contact email above.

## 8. Security

The backend uses API-key authentication for GPT Action requests and stores artifacts in controlled cloud storage. No system can be guaranteed completely secure, but the workflow is designed around scoped run IDs, agent permissions, and phase-level artifact controls.

## 9. Reviewer responsibilities

Reviewers must not submit material they are not authorized to process.

Reviewers must not submit sensitive personal data, privileged legal material, trade secrets, credentials, payment information, medical information, or other restricted material unless the workflow has been separately approved for that use.

